<subSubSection lastPageId="17" lastPageNumber="488" pageId="16" pageNumber="487" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,1338,2011]" lastBlockId="17.[151,1436,151,357]" lastPageId="17" lastPageNumber="488" pageId="16" pageNumber="487">
As we anticipated (
<bibRefCitation author="Cock" box="[368,650,1338,1363]" pageId="16" pageNumber="487" refString="Cock, M. J. W. &amp; Congdon, T. C. E. (2011 b) Observations on the biology of Afrotropical Hesperiidae (Lepidoptera) principally from Kenya. Part 3. Pyrginae: Celaenorrhinini. Zootaxa, 3033, 1 - 67." type="journal article" year="2011" yearSuffix="b">Cock &amp; Congdon 2011b</bibRefCitation>
), 
<taxonomicName authority="(Butler)" authorityName="Butler" authorityYear="1911" box="[670,898,1338,1363]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Apallaga" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="487" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="biseriata">
<emphasis box="[670,801,1338,1363]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="487">A. biseriata</emphasis>
(Butler)
</taxonomicName>
is a valid species rather than a subspecies of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Fabricius)" authorityName="Fabricius" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Celaenorrhinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="487" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="galenus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="487">A. galenus</emphasis>
(Fabricius)
</taxonomicName>
. The population from eastern Kenya which we treated as 
<taxonomicName box="[1084,1322,1374,1399]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Celaenorrhinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="487" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="galenus" subSpecies="biseriata">
<emphasis box="[1084,1322,1374,1399]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="487">C. galenus biseriata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Cock" pageId="16" pageNumber="487" refString="Cock, M. J. W. &amp; Congdon, T. C. E. (2011 b) Observations on the biology of Afrotropical Hesperiidae (Lepidoptera) principally from Kenya. Part 3. Pyrginae: Celaenorrhinini. Zootaxa, 3033, 1 - 67." type="journal article" year="2011" yearSuffix="b">Cock &amp; Congdon 2011b, pp. 28–32, Figures 27–30</bibRefCitation>
) is now treated as 
<taxonomicName authority="(Hampson)" authorityName="Hampson" authorityYear="1911" box="[899,1294,1410,1435]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Apallaga" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="487" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="biseriata" subSpecies="maculata">
<emphasis box="[899,1152,1410,1435]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="487">A. biseriata maculata</emphasis>
(Hampson)
</taxonomicName>
, which was described from the Sabaki River, eastern Kenya (
<bibRefCitation author="Hampson" box="[709,886,1447,1471]" pageId="16" pageNumber="487" refString="Hampson, G. F. (1891) Lepidoptera from the Sabaki River, East Africa, with descriptions of new species. Annals and Magazine of Natural History, 6 (7), 179 - 184. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222939109460594" type="journal article" year="1891">Hampson 1891</bibRefCitation>
), and occurs from southern Kenya to Zimbabwe (
<bibRefCitation author="Libert" box="[158,302,1482,1507]" pageId="16" pageNumber="487" refString="Libert, M. (2014) Sur la taxonomie du genre Celaenorrhinus Hubner en Afrique (Lepidoptera, Hesperiidae). M. J. B. S. A. S. - Librairie Top Duck, Amboise, France, 272 pp., 26 pl." type="book" year="2014">Libert 2014</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authority="Collins &amp; Congdon" authorityName="Collins &amp; Congdon" authorityYear="1998" box="[339,882,1482,1507]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Celaenorrhinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="487" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="handmani">
<emphasis box="[339,639,1482,1507]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="487">Celaenorrhinus handmani</emphasis>
Collins &amp; Congdon
</taxonomicName>
which we treated as a valid species (
<bibRefCitation author="Cock" pageId="16" pageNumber="487" refString="Cock, M. J. W. &amp; Congdon, T. C. E. (2011 b) Observations on the biology of Afrotropical Hesperiidae (Lepidoptera) principally from Kenya. Part 3. Pyrginae: Celaenorrhinini. Zootaxa, 3033, 1 - 67." type="journal article" year="2011" yearSuffix="b">Cock &amp; Congdon 2011b, pp. 32–34, Figures 31–33</bibRefCitation>
) is considered a synonym of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Libert 2014)" authorityName="Libert" authorityYear="2014" baseAuthorityName="Libert" baseAuthorityYear="2014" box="[972,1380,1518,1543]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Apallaga" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="487" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="biseriata" subSpecies="maculata">
<emphasis box="[972,1216,1518,1543]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="487">A. biseriata maculata</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Libert" box="[1232,1372,1518,1543]" pageId="16" pageNumber="487" refString="Libert, M. (2014) Sur la taxonomie du genre Celaenorrhinus Hubner en Afrique (Lepidoptera, Hesperiidae). M. J. B. S. A. S. - Librairie Top Duck, Amboise, France, 272 pp., 26 pl." type="book" year="2014">Libert 2014</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. We collected both populations from 
<taxonomicName box="[513,742,1554,1579]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Acanthaceae" genus="Hypoestes" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="16" pageNumber="487" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="forskaolii">
<emphasis box="[513,742,1554,1579]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="487">Hypoestes forskaolii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName box="[757,904,1554,1579]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Acanthaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="16" pageNumber="487" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Acanthaceae</taxonomicName>
) and saw no diagnostic differences between the early stages. However, when the barcodes for this material are examined, it is not so clear-cut, as individuals named as A. 
<taxonomicName authority="Strand, 1911" authorityName="Strand" authorityYear="1911" baseAuthorityName="Libert" baseAuthorityYear="2014" box="[326,546,1626,1651]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Apallaga" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="487" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="biseriata" subSpecies="maculata">
<emphasis box="[326,546,1626,1651]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="487">biseriata maculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be found within several different barcode clusters, including BINs BOLD:ABY8703, BOLD:AAQ3589, BOLD:ACE5675, BOLD:ACE3207 and BOLD:ABY8700 (BINs are hereafter referred to by the last seven characters), mostly in isolation, but in one case alongside individuals of other species with identical barcodes. We note in particular that specimens from Mufindi, Tanzania, the type locality of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Collins &amp; Congdon" authorityYear="1998" box="[151,296,1770,1795]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Celaenorrhinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="487" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="handmani">
<emphasis box="[151,296,1770,1795]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="487">C. handmani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are placed in a separate BIN (ACE3207) together with two specimens from Ethiopia which appear to be a different species with the same barcode. The bulk of Tanzanian specimens form a separate compact cluster (ABY8703 from Kimboza, Kihansi, Rondo Plateau, Rubeho, Rondo and the Shimba Hills, Kenya). TCEC’s observations on 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Collins &amp; Congdon" authorityYear="1998" box="[340,486,1878,1903]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Celaenorrhinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="487" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="handmani">
<emphasis box="[340,486,1878,1903]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="487">A. handmani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Strand, 1911" authorityName="Strand" authorityYear="1911" box="[546,815,1878,1903]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Apallaga" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="487" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="biseriatus" subSpecies="maculatus">
<emphasis box="[546,815,1878,1903]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="487">A. biseriatus maculatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
indicate allopatric populations at different elevations. 
<taxonomicName authority="Strand, 1911" authorityName="Strand" authorityYear="1911" box="[151,502,1914,1939]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Apallaga" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="487" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="biseriatus" subSpecies="maculatus">
<emphasis box="[151,502,1914,1939]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="487">Apallaga biseriatus maculatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurs at lower elevations and seems to occur no higher than at 
<quantity box="[1280,1358,1915,1939]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.8" pageId="16" pageNumber="487" unit="m" value="1800.0">1800m</quantity>
in the Chyulu Hills (
<bibRefCitation author="Van" box="[310,530,1951,1975]" pageId="16" pageNumber="487" refString="Van Someren, V. G. L. (1939) Butterflies of the Chyulu Range. A systematic list of the species taken by the Museum Expedition to the hills. April - July 1938. Journal of the East Africa and Uganda Natural History Society, 14, 130 - 151." type="journal article" year="1939">Van Someren 1939</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authority="Strand, 1911" authorityName="Collins" authorityYear="2017" baseAuthorityName="Collins &amp; Congdon" box="[557,779,1950,1975]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Apallaga" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="487" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="handmani">
<emphasis box="[557,779,1950,1975]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="487">Apallaga handmani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a moderate to high elevation species, so their ranges do not overlap. 
<taxonomicName authority="Strand, 1911" authorityName="Collins" authorityYear="2017" baseAuthorityName="Collins &amp; Congdon" box="[308,532,1986,2011]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Apallaga" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="487" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="handmani">
<emphasis box="[308,532,1986,2011]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="487">Apallaga handmani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was thought to occur as low as 
<quantity box="[914,992,1986,2011]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.45" pageId="16" pageNumber="487" unit="m" value="1450.0">1450m</quantity>
on Mt. Mabu in Mozambique (at that latitude, the elevation is equivalent to 
<quantity box="[584,662,152,176]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.8" pageId="17" pageNumber="488" unit="m" value="1800.0">1800m</quantity>
or more at the equator), but this population comes out as a different BIN (ACE5675) so there may be additional allopatric diversity here. Again, more work is needed to understand this situation and reconcile taxonomy with barcode patterns (cf. 
<taxonomicName authority="Strand, 1911" authorityName="in Cock &amp; Congdon" authorityYear="2011" box="[878,1006,223,248]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Apallaga" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="488" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="opalinus">
<emphasis box="[878,1006,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="488">A. opalinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Strand, 1911" authorityName="Libert" authorityYear="2014" box="[1063,1221,223,248]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Apallaga" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="488" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kakamegae">
<emphasis box="[1063,1221,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="488">A. kakamegae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
above). However, we think the barcode difference justifies reinstating 
<taxonomicName authority="Strand, 1911" authorityName="Collins" authorityYear="2017" baseAuthorityName="Collins &amp; Congdon" box="[740,886,260,285]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Apallaga" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="488" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="handmani" status="stat. rev.">
<emphasis box="[740,886,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="488">C. handmani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[893,996,260,285]" pageId="17" pageNumber="488">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[893,996,260,285]" pageId="17" pageNumber="488">stat. rev.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
as a good species, although not all the type series of 
<taxonomicName authority="Strand, 1911" authorityName="Collins" authorityYear="2017" baseAuthorityName="Collins &amp; Congdon" box="[307,450,295,320]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Apallaga" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="488" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="handmani">
<emphasis box="[307,450,295,320]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="488">A. handmani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are likely to represent this species rather than previously unrecognised, very similar but genetically distinct, allopatric species, such as the population from Mozambique mentioned above.
</paragraph>
